# NO UNNECESSARY API ROUTES

This project already has 176+ API routes. Most should have been server actions. STOP adding more.

## When to use a server action (DEFAULT)

- Saving a vote, review, rating, bookmark
- Incrementing a counter (clicks, views, likes)
- Sending an email or contact form
- Any simple DB read/write triggered by a user action
- Any CRUD that only your own components consume

```typescript
// GOOD: server action in lib/actions/
'use server';
import connectDB from '@/lib/db/mongodb';
import { SomeModel } from '@/lib/models';

export async function trackClick(id: string) {
  await connectDB();
  await SomeModel.findByIdAndUpdate(id, { $inc: { clicks: 1 } });
}
```

## When an API route is ACTUALLY needed

- External webhooks (payment providers, cron services POST to your URL)
- `sendBeacon()` tracking (only works with URLs, not server actions)
- Endpoints consumed by external systems (mobile apps, third-party integrations)
- File uploads requiring special request body handling
- Infinite scroll / pagination fetched client-side with `fetch()`

## PROHIBITED

- Creating an API route "just in case" or "for flexibility"
- Creating an API route for a simple DB insert that one component uses
- Creating multiple API routes that do the same thing (e.g. 8 separate "increment counter" routes)
- Creating an API route when a server component prop or server action works

## Why this matters

- Every API route = a separate Vercel serverless function = cold start cost
- Every API route = a file to maintain, debug, and read context for
- Every `fetch()` call = HTTP round-trip overhead vs direct server action call
- More files = slower builds, higher Cursor token usage, harder debugging
- API routes are public endpoints = security surface to protect

## Rule of thumb

If the data flows from YOUR component to YOUR database and back, use a server action.
If an EXTERNAL system needs to call you, use an API route.
